                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> It will probably just make the item itself 'nodrop', rather than be restricted to nodrop items.  This way, you can customize an item that you like and intend to keep and make it more personal.  At high enough levels, with enough 'scrolls' or 'doo-dads' or 'doohickies' there is no reason to imagine that focus effects, flowing thought, hps/mana, and other goodies wouldn't be included.  <br /><br />They can restrict the types of benefits you get to the various levels of 'items' like they did with parchments/runes in PoP.  So that a low end guild or player isn't picking up 'embroidered golden parchments' that allow +30 hps.  Instead, they'd get 'faded cloth scroll' or whatever that gives +5 hps.  <br /><br />And, I'd guess that it affects the item.  Why?  Because, this is best for the long-term health of the game.  If it affected slots, which is what everyone most likely wants, then after X turn ins, you'd be done with the expansion with nothing else to do.   <br /><br />Instead, in order to prevent mud-flation and making the expansion obsolete, the modifications go on items.  That way, you choose particular items that you want to improve.  The downside is that you are pretty much forced to keep that item.  The upside is that the game stays healthier.  This also has the effect of taking items out of 'circulation' which again reduces mudflation and improves long term viability.  <br /><br />Take Zland heart for instance.  That's commonly argued about.  Uber players say it's worthless, younger players all think it's great.  Now, if you could add +50 hps, +50 mana, FT1, and say, clicky feign death or something to zland heart, and still have the regen, .... then you may consider using it.<br /><br />And certianly, once someone invests time and effort into an item, there is much less incentive to sell it.  That is assuming that they provide a way to 'unbond' the item so that it becomes droppable.  <br /><br />/ponder possibilities<br /><br />Wyndaria.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                     <td colspan="2" valign="bottom" align="left" height="20"><hr noshade size="2"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"></td></tr><td width="100%" nowrap>
